Treasury Secretary James Baker isurging Congress to pass legislation promptly to raise theceiling on U.S. debt the United States can borrow, Senatemajority leader Robert Byrd said.    Byrd told reporters Baker visited him late Friday to urgeCongress not to add time-delaying amendments to the debtceiling bill that Congress must pass before May 15. Byrd, aDemocrat, said he agrees but said others may want amendments.    The current ceiling of 2.3 trillion (2,300 billion) dlrsdrops on May 15 to 2.1 trillion dlrs, a level considered toolow for U.S. borrowing. Reuter&#3;